                                Report abuseTranscript of DAVID BUSSMate Preferences & Mating StrategiesDAVID BUSSVocabularyMethodSurveyed 10,000 people from 37 culturesAsked what people looked for in a mateResults matched parental investment theory: females placed emphasis on mates' success, males on looksAsked undergraduate college students about consenting to sex with someone they have only known for a short timeMales more likely than females to consentUsing a variety of research methods and samples, the same mating preference and priority differences b/w males and females were found CriticismCan come up with different explanations for findings on sexual behavior Ex. the emphasis on finding a mate with good resources could be caused by cultural and economic forcesDoesn't take non-evolutionary and non-adaptive factors into accountMate preferences are subjective; not all males prefer the expected characteristics in females, and vice versaCan vary across different culturesBiography & EducationBuss was born on April 14, 1953 in Indianapolis, Indiana.His father, Arnold H. Buss, was a psychologist, influencing his son's motivation to pursue the same field.Buss attended the University of Texas, first focusing on literary fiction and flute performance, but later developed a keen interest in evolutionary psychology.Buss earned his Bachelor of the Arts Degree in psychology at the University of Texas in 1976 and his Ph. D. at the University of California at Berkeley in 1981.Consistent w/ evolutionary theoryHumans inherit mating strategies of ancestors that led to our ancestor's reproductive success through sexual selectionMen find mates w/ good reproductive potential (more youthful &attractive)Women find mates that are more dependable and willing to invest resources for family (emphasized intelligence, ambition, income, social status)Evolutionary Theory: the idea that people choose mates based on chances of reproductive successSexual selection: mechanism through which traits that increase the probability of successful reproduction increase in frequencyMating strategies: long-term mating (i.e marriage)short-term mating (i.e short sexual encounter)Parental investment: refers to what each sex has to invest- in terms of time, energy, survival risk, and forgone opportunities - to produce and nurture offspringCareerWorks CitedPressnell, Faith. "David Buss." Psychology History. N.p., Dec. 1999. Web. 09 Feb. 2015. <http://www.muskingum.edu/~psych/psycweb/history/buss.htm>.Thumpaholden. "Terms, Psych of Personality Ch 12 - Buss." Flashcards. N.p., n.d. Web. 09 Feb. 2015. <http://quizlet.com/2433078/terms-psych-of-personality-ch-12-buss-flash-cards/>."David Buss." Social Psychology Network. N.p., 23 Feb. 2009. Web. 4 Feb. 2015. <http://buss.socialpsychology.org/>. Weiten, Wayne. "Motivation and Emotion." Psychology: Themes and Variations. 8th ed. N.p.: n.p., n.d. N. pag. Print.After receiving his PhD at Berkeley, Buss became Assistant Professor at Harvard University.Taught at University of Texas, then became a professor at University of MichiganBuss's work is honored in the psychology community; won an APA Distinguished Scientific Award for his articles on evolutionary psychology and sexAuthored many books about sex, desire, and emotional conflictsFocus is primarily on gender psychology and differences between the sexesDAVID BUSSBY ALICE KUAN & ANNA LIPD. 3 Full transcriptMore presentations by
    
        
